.SH DATABASE
.SS Loading an existing Database
.sp
To load in a previous database, you run the db_load script.
.sp
From the game directory you would type:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
\&./db_load data/netrhost.gdbm yourflatfilehere data/netrhost.db.new
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBNOTE:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
You may also do: ./Startmush
Then you just follow the prompts to load in your flatfile there.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
If you wish to have #1\(aqs password reset to \(aqNyctasia\(aq please add this
to the bottom of your netrhost.conf file:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
newpass_god 777
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
The caveat is that you must not have any netrhost.db* or netrhost.gdbm* files
in your data directory prior to loading it in.  It\(aqll error out if previous
files exist.  So you will need to move all files that start with netrhost.db*
and all files that start with netrhost.gdbm* to another directory.
.sp
Your flatfile tends to be named \(aqnetrhost.db.flat\(aq which is in your data
directory.  You can, however, name your flatfile anything you want and have
it in any directory you want.
.sp
To make a flatfile in game, you just issue @dump/flat.  You can specify
a filename after it, otherwise it assumes the name \(aqnetrhost.db.flat\(aq.
.SS Converting a flatfile database for use in RhostMUSH
.sp
In the ~/Server/convert directory there is a script called \(aqdoconvert.sh\(aq
.sp
This script will convert most flatfiles from existing mush engines to
RhostMUSH.  The exception is PennMUSH 1.8.0 and later.  For this there is a
BETA converter penn18x_converter.tgz.  This is proven to work, most of the time,
with codebases between 1.8.0 and 1.8.2.  It has not been fully vetted with
the latest PennMUSH databases.  Our apologies.
.sp
To convert a non\-pennmush game (or a pennmush 1.7.4 or earlier), you first
need a valid flatfile of the game you\(aqre wanting to convert.  Please refer
to the documentatation of the mush engine in question (MUX, Penn 1.7, TM2/3)
on how to do this.  Once you have it type::
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
\&./doconvert.sh FLATFILETOCONVERT FLATFILEOUTPUT
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
In this instance, FLATFILETOCONVERT will be the filename (with full path) to
the flatfile you are wishing to convert.
.sp
The FLATFILEOUTPUT is anyfilename you wish to name the RhostMUSH converted
flatfile.  I suggest netrhost_converted.db.flat so you know by the name
what it is.
.sp
Follow what it asks for and just let it do its thing.
.SS Note about Compiling
.sp
If you are importing a MUX2 flatfile, make ABSOLUTELY SURE that you select
mux passwords as a compatibility option, or you will NOT BE ABLE to log in
to players as the password will not be recognizeable.
.sp
Make sure to keep QDBM selected as it\(aqs a much more stable database engine
that does not have attribute limit restrictions like GDBM does.
.sp
If you are converting from a Penn, TinyMUSH, or MUX database, make sure you
drill down into the LBUF section and select, at minimum, 8K lbufs.  You likely
want that anyway as it gives you far more room for attribute content storage.
.sp
You can go up to 32K safely.  While 64k is safe and does work, there are issues
with networking and older routers that use a 32K TCP buffer size that can
at times cut off the data as overflow resulting in output to the end\-point
players not receiving their data.  So it is strongly recommended not to go
above 32K in lbuffer size.
.sp
Go ahead and select 64 char attributes.  It allows you to have 64 characters
for attribute names.  It\(aqs handy to have.
.sp
If you wish at this point to set up mysql and/or sqlite, you  may do so.
Yes, you can use them in parallel without any issue.
.SH GETTING STARTED
.SS What to type to get the basics running if you did not choose a pre\-existing flatfile
.sp
If you decided to get a bare\-bone configuration, you will find your mush has just two things.  The #1 (God) player and the starting room #0.  That\(aqs it.
.SS Login to #1 from the connect screen
.sp
Nyctasia is the default password:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
co #1 Nyctasia
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Change #1\(aqs password to something you\(aqll remember but is hard to guess
.sp
Note: yourpasswordgoeshere can be any password you choose.  Choose well:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@password Nyctasia=YOURPASSWORDGOESHERE
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Master Room
.sp
At this point you should create your master room:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@dig Master Room
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBNOTE:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
Reason: You need a master room to contain global $commands for players
^listens are not global for intentional reasons.  It\(aqs far too much overhead for far too minimal gains that few people need or use.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Flag and protect Master Room
.sp
It will return a dbref#, it should be #2 if you\(aqve not created anything else:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@set #2=safe ind halt float
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Player Holder Characters
.sp
Feel free to change the password to what you want
.sp
\fBNOTE:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
Reason: You will want to chown global room or global areas to a given bitlevel and a method to keep organized.
Note: wizhelp control will give you a complete breakdown of what each bit can do.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Immortal Holder
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@pcreate ImmHolder=abc123
@set *Immholder=no_connect !wanderer immortal
@badsite *immholder=*
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Royalty/Wizard Holder
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@pcreate WizHolder=abc123
@set *wizholder=no_connect !wanderer royalty
@badsite *wizholder=*
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Councilor/Admin Holder
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@pcreate AdminHolder=abc123
@set *adminholder=no_connect !wanderer councilor
@badsite *adminholder=*
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Architect/Staff Holder
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@pcreate StaffHolder=abc123
@set *staffholder=no_connect !wanderer architect
@badsite *staffholder=*
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Guildmaster/Lead Holder
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@pcreate GuildHolder=abc123
@set *guildholder=no_connect !wanderer guildmaster
@badsite *guildholder=*
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Chown #0 (The starting room) and #2 (The Master room) to immholder
.sp
\fBNOTE:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
#0 you can chown to a different bitlevel if you want, but the master room should always be owned by an immortal
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@chown/preserve #0=*immholder
@chown/preserve #2=*immholder
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Create yourself your own immortal player then log off #1 and into this immortal player
.sp
\fBNOTE:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
Pick what you want for playername and playerpassword
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@pcreate PLAYERNAME=PLAYERPASSWORD
@set *playername=!wanderer immortal
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Log out of #1 and log into your immortal player
.sp
\fBNOTE:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
Use the playername and password you created in the step before
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
LOGOUT
co PLAYERNAME PLAYERPASSWORD
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Create your guest characters
.sp
\fBNOTE:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
Feel free to change the description if you want
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@dolist lnum(1,10)={@pcreate Guest##=guest;@set *Guest##=guest;@adisconnect *Guest##=home;@lock *Guest##=*Guest##;@desc *Guest##=A Stranger in a strange land.}
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Dig a closet to store important objects but non\-master room
.sp
\fBNOTE:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
name it anything you want, just remember it.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@dig Closet
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Set the flags on the closet and ownership of it
.sp
\fBNOTE:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
Use the dbref# that it returned when digging the closet and not #123
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@set #123=inh safe ind float
@chown/pres #123=*immholder
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Create an Admin object for future ease of customization
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@create AdminObject
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Set the flags on the admin object and ownership and location
.sp
\fBNOTE:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
this object must be immortal owned.  Use the dbref# returned previously instead of #123
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBNOTE:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
Use the closet dbref# instead of #234
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@set AdminObject=halt safe ind
@chown/pres #123=*immholder
@tel adminobject=#234
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Add admin object to configuration
.sp
Modify the netrhost.conf file with the following line at the bottom after the line \(aq# define local alises here\(aq where you replace 123 with the dbref# of the admin object that you made:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
admin_object 123
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Reboot your mush to load up the change for the admin object
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@reboot
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Do @admin/list to see if it shows the admin object
.sp
\fBNOTE:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
do wizhelp @admin for more information on how to use this
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@admin/list
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Load in all the various softcode that you want
.sp
This is client dependant based on whatever method it uses to load softcode.
.SS Myrddin MushCron
.sp
Load in the Myrddin Mush Cron.
It\(aqs a very handy piece of software and strongly suggested to do so.  You can find this in the \(aqMushcode\(aq directory off the main Rhost directory.
Filename:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
~/Rhost/Mushcode/MyrddinCRON
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBNOTE:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
The globalroom() function returns the dbref# of the master room.  Handy!
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@chown/preserve the myrddin mush cron to immholder, then move to maste room.
@chown/pres Myrddin=*Immholder
@tel Myrddin=#234 (where #234 is the dbref# of your code closet)
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS AshCom
.sp
Load in default softcoded comsystem.  This is PennMUSH and MUX/TM3 compatible.
Filename:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
~/Rhost/Mushcode/comsys
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Chown the Comsystem and everything inside it to immholder:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@chown/pres ChanSys=*Immholder
@dolist lcon(chansys)=@chown/pres ##=*immholder
@tel Chansys=globalroom()
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Mail Wrappers
.sp
Load in mail wrappers if you want MUX/TM3 and/or Penn mail wrapping.
Filename (MUX/TM3):
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
~/Rhost/Mushcode/mailwrappers/muxmail.wrap
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Filename (Penn):
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
~/Rhost/Mushcode/mailwrappers/pennmail.wrap
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Chown to immholder:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
@chown/pres MUX=*Immholder
@chown/pres Penn=*Immholder
@tel/list mux penn=globalroom()
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Myrddin BBS
.sp
Load in Myrddin\(aqs BBS
Filename:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
~/Rhost/Mushcode/MyrddinBBS
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Chown to immholder and the contents of it as well:
